High availability does NOT guarantee zero data loss.
Fault tolerance does.

Why data loss can happen in High Availability

High availability focuses on:

Keeping the system up

Serving requests

Minimizing downtime

It does not always guarantee:

All writes are safely replicated before a failure

Example

Primary node receives a write

Before data replicates to secondary nodes

Primary crashes

Secondary takes over without that last write

â¡ï¸ System is available, but last data is lost

Fault Tolerance (contrast)

Fault tolerance ensures:

Data is replicated safely

System can recover without losing data

Writes are acknowledged only after replication

â¡ï¸ No data loss

| Feature              | High Availability | Fault Tolerance |
| -------------------- | ----------------- | --------------- |
| System stays online  | âœ…                 | âœ…               |
| Handles node failure | âœ…                 | âœ…               |
| Data loss possible   | âš ï¸ Yes            | âŒ No            |


â€œHigh availability ensures uptime, but it may allow some data loss. Fault tolerance ensures correctness and no data loss even during failures.â€




#######


First: what uptime & downtime mean

Uptime = time the system is available and serving requests

Downtime = time the system is unavailable

Example:

99.9% uptime â‰ˆ ~8.7 hours downtime per year

99.99% uptime â‰ˆ ~52 minutes downtime per year

Now, fix the misunderstanding ğŸ‘‡

âŒ â€œIn fault tolerance, uptime is 0â€
âœ… No â€” fault-tolerant systems also aim for very high uptime

Fault tolerance is not about being offline.
Itâ€™s about continuing to work correctly even when failures occur.

Correct comparison
High Availability (HA)

Goal: Minimize downtime

System stays online by:

Redirecting traffic

Failing over to another node

Might lose a small amount of data

Uptime: Very high
Downtime: Very small

Fault Tolerance (FT)

Goal: No data loss + correct behavior

System continues operating even during failures

Often requires:

More replicas

Synchronous replication

Stronger guarantees

Uptime: Very high (often same or better than HA)
Downtime: Near zero

Key correction (important for interview)

Fault tolerance is a superset of high availability, not the opposite.

All fault-tolerant systems are highly available

Not all highly available systems are fault-tolerant

One-line interview answer (memorize)

â€œHigh availability minimizes downtime, while fault tolerance ensures the system continues to operate correctly without data loss during failures â€” both aim for high uptime.â€

Ultra-simple analogy

High availability â†’ backup generator turns on quickly (lights may flicker)

Fault tolerance â†’ lights never flicker at a